A Deed by which Alexander Innes of Cottis renuncis, dischargis and overgives in favour of Jhone Bischop of Moray, the office of Constabularie of the fortalice and castle of Spynie, yairdis orcheardis and all and sundrie utheris within the precinct of the said place, which umquhil Alexander Lord of Spynie and Lord of the Regality thereof3—by his charter‚ of the dait at the Cannogait the 18 December 1599, confirmed by a charter under the great seal, 25 December 1599, and by a charter of umquhil Alexander Bischop of Moray with consent of the deane and chapter, of the dait at Elgin [ ] day of Junii 1607,—granted to umquhil Jhone Innes of Lewchers in lyfrent and to the said Alexander Innes in see, together with ane see of ane hundreth pounds yeirlie out of the fruits profits and dewties of the said lordship and rega- litie and of the lands, baronies, tounes and fischingis perteining to the bischoprick besor the act ofannexatioun ; with the privilege of keiping ofthe wod, schaw or forrest of Spynie, with 9 bouis victual for the same ; with the keiping of the Loch of Spynie and power to take and ssay fisches swimming therein ; and with power to take peittes and uther feuall in the Laverock moss and in the mures adjacent thereto; and all uther fies, dewties, privileges, casualities and immuni- ties perteining to the said office of Constabularie. A procuratory of refignatioun is contained at the end. WVitness'es ΜΓ Jhone Kinneir and Mr Francis Hay writer to his Majesties signet, William Moray of Dunern, and Androw Aytoun of Logie advocat.
